Here's how to implement all three:

**1 & 2 — Guard navigation with a confirmation dialog**

In `AppShell.xaml.cs`, override `OnNavigating` and use `GetDeferral()` for the async dialog:

```csharp
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

> **Key:** You must call `GetDeferral()` *before* the `await` and `deferral.Complete()` *after* — otherwise the navigation completes before your dialog returns.

**3 — Custom "Cancel" back button**

In `EditProductPage.xaml`, attach a `BackButtonBehavior`:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                            Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

In your ViewModel (or code-behind):

```csharp
[RelayCommand]
async Task Cancel()
{
    // This triggers OnNavigating, so the guard dialog still fires
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

Because `GoToAsync("..")` is a `Pop` navigation, the `OnNavigating` guard above will intercept it and show the confirmation dialog automatically — no duplicate logic needed.
